        "text": "A source package for R will be named `&lt;package&gt;_&lt;version&gt;.tar.gz`, nothing more. A Linux binary package for R will have extra suffixes in the file name, such as `_R_x86_64_pc-linux-gnu`. A source package will likely have `*.R` text files in the `&lt;package_name&gt;\/R\/` directory inside it. A binary package will instead have one text file saying it's from `nspackloader.R` and two binary files, `*.rdb` and `*.rdx`. A Linux binary package may have compiled code in `libs\/*.so` (and no `src\/`); a source package will instead have source code in `src\/` (and no `libs\/`).\nThere are also Linux packages in the other sense, `*.deb` and `*.rpm` (and other) files that make up a GNU\/Linux installation. Confusingly, they could also contain binary packages for R. (For example, Debian and Ubuntu users could install a binary build of quadprog from the `r-cran-quadprog*.deb` package instead of running `install.packages(\"quadprog\")` and compiling it from source.)\n\nIt could be possible to enable Windows Subsystem for Linux and run the Linux version of R inside it, but that may require even more access to the Internet in order to install dependencies (automatically via <https:\/\/eddelbuettel.github.io\/r2u\/|r2u>\/<https:\/\/copr.fedorainfracloud.org\/coprs\/iucar\/cran\/|cran2copr> or semi-manually) and thus increase your attack surface. On the other hand, if you have a local mirror of Ubuntu repositories and can arrange to have a local mirror of pre-built packages for R, running Ubuntu in WSL should mostly solve your R package problems.\n\nA better link about creating a CRAN mirror (which will include pre-built packages for Windows) is &lt;https:\/\/cran.r-project.org\/mirror-howto.html&gt;.",
